r rights to make decisions for themselves as to what they can and can not afford to do for their children. In the long run, the degradation of the public school system will eventually have a higher cost to the economy and the ability of those wealthy people to harvest resources (educated and qualified people) because their unwillingness to commit and support the greater effort will come back to haunt them with the downside of things. Seems like a situation of darned if you do and darned if you don't. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="813" language="en" documentId="3003" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="amazed4570" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:53PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="3" thumbsDown="0" origId="3003" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="813"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>